00:05:25.283 --> 00:05:27.730
<v Hans> So a lot of you
probably have an understanding

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:31.280
of what accessibility is, but
because we're coming more

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:34.710
from a privacy expertise, we want
to at least cover what privacy is.

00:05:34.710 --> 00:05:38.610
So privacy is generally defined
as being left alone, or the state

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:40.690
of being free from
observation by others.

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:44.300
I will say, though, that privacy,
I think, means different things

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:45.220
to different people.

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:48.620
But really, what's
happening here in the world is

00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:52.000
that we have governments
protecting and regulating

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.060
the personal information
of their people.

00:05:54.650 --> 00:05:58.220
So personal information is
anything that could be used

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:02.436
to identify an individual, that is
personally identifiable information,

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:04.515
otherwise known as PII.

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:07.380
So governments around the
world are creating regulations

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:10.560
to protect people's PII
so that website owners

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:13.360
or companies can't just
take that personal information

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:15.530
and do whatever
they want with it.

00:06:15.530 --> 00:06:17.740
Here in the States, we
actually have a friend visiting

00:06:17.740 --> 00:06:19.826
from the UK over the last week.

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:22.590
And the moment he got to
America, he started getting

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:24.565
about 30 spam calls a day.

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:26.800
And that is an infringement
on privacy, at least

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:30.720
in many people's opinions, and
that is what governments are trying

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:33.366
to help regulate and
prevent from happening.

00:06:33.390 --> 00:06:35.890
<v Donata> Yes, and
privacy basically means

00:06:35.890 --> 00:06:38.610
that people can determine
the level of interaction

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:41.176
that they would like to
have with a company online.

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:44.220
So if I want to receive email
marketing from a company,

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:46.026
I can say, Yes, I
would like to receive it.

00:06:46.050 --> 00:06:48.406
Or I can say, No, I
would not like to receive it.

00:06:48.430 --> 00:06:50.500
Or I would like to receive
text messages from you,

00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:52.306
or maybe I don't
want to do that.

00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:54.606
So it's a level of interaction
that they would like to have

00:06:54.630 --> 00:06:55.730
with a company online.

00:06:55.730 --> 00:06:58.850
<v Hans> And there's nothing wrong
with collecting personal information.

00:06:58.850 --> 00:07:01.236
In fact, I always advocate
that's a great thing.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:04.220
What we need to understand
today as website owners is

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:06.760
that we need to get
consent first prior to collecting

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:09.610
people's information, and also
making sure our policies are

00:07:09.610 --> 00:07:11.810
up to date with accurate
disclosures you're required

00:07:11.810 --> 00:07:13.320
to make under applicable laws.

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:15.700
<v Donata> Yes, and
what is accessibility?

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:19.476
So accessibility is defined as
the practice of making information,

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:23.100
activities, and environment
sensible, meaningful, and usable for

00:07:23.100 --> 00:07:24.700
as many people as possible.

00:07:25.230 --> 00:07:28.580
So it basically means that people
can interact, comprehend, navigate,

00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:31.040
and contribute to
the online world.

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:35.636
Privacy and accessibility, even
though they're two distinct concepts,

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:39.040
they do intersect together to
create a digital world that is open

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:41.986
to everyone, regardless
of their disability status

00:07:42.010 --> 00:07:43.800
or their privacy preferences.

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:47.486
Accessibility can
interact with privacy

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:50.300
because it can make
privacy-centric features compliant

00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:54.350
with privacy laws, because
privacy laws do require accessibility.

00:07:54.910 --> 00:07:58.900
Privacy can make accessibility
features usable without somebody needing

00:07:58.900 --> 00:08:02.630
to sacrifice their personal
preferences on their privacy,

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:05.926
meaning they don't have to
sacrifice the level of interaction

00:08:05.950 --> 00:08:08.176
that they would like to
have with companies online,

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:11.580
and they don't have to sacrifice
their privacy rights as well.

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:13.820
<v Hans> And we have a
handful of examples to go

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:17.030
through today to kind of
really instill this concept

00:08:17.030 --> 00:08:18.770
into everyone's minds today.

00:08:18.770 --> 00:08:20.452
<v Donata> Absolutely.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:23.700
So why do privacy
and accessibility matter?

00:08:24.610 --> 00:08:27.286
We have a couple of
reasons as to why, but first,

00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:28.930
it's really the
right thing to do.

00:08:29.530 --> 00:08:32.270
Presenting your website
visitors with an accessible

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:35.840
and privacy-conscious
website is the right thing to do.

00:08:36.250 --> 00:08:39.610
So you should allow people to
clearly see privacy information

00:08:39.610 --> 00:08:43.410
and make privacy-related
selections to allow them to determine

00:08:43.410 --> 00:08:45.690
how they would like to
interact with you and how.

00:08:46.180 --> 00:08:48.086
And then providing
an accessible website.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.438
Make sure that everyone can use the
website

00:08:50.462 --> 00:08:52.400
without difficulty or frustration.

00:08:52.425 --> 00:08:55.565
So they both work together
to make a better web.

00:08:56.710 --> 00:09:00.020
Secondly, it's actually good for
business to care about privacy.

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:05.696
So if you think about 10 years
ago, privacy wasn't really a big deal.

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:09.090
People didn't really look at
privacy policies, or look to see

00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:10.990
if somebody had a
cookie consent banner.

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:15.226
They didn't care if you track them via
Google Analytics or Facebook Pixel.

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:18.190
At least for most people,
but that has changed.

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:22.010
And that really changed with
the Cambridge Analytica scandal.

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:26.220
Cambridge Analytica took the
personal information of millions

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:28.976
of Facebook users
without their permission

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.496
and used it to manipulate
political advertisements.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:35.880
And that really brought privacy to
the forefront of consumers' minds.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.960
They really realized, If I provide
my information to a company,

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:41.810
they can do pretty
much anything with it,

00:09:41.810 --> 00:09:43.876
and there's nothing
I can do about that.

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:47.436
And that's where all these privacy
laws and regulations really come from.

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:50.190
Today, people are actually
more concerned about their privacy

00:09:50.190 --> 00:09:53.310
than ever before, and they
are willing to make decisions on

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:56.586
who to do business with
based on privacy practices.

00:09:56.610 --> 00:09:58.900
And there's a lot of studies
that talk about this, but two

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:03.240
that I wanted to highlight,
32% have switched companies

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:06.770
because of privacy practices, meaning
that they went from one company

00:10:06.770 --> 00:10:08.920
to another because
of privacy concerns.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:12.190
And seven in ten Canadians
refused to provide data

00:10:12.190 --> 00:10:15.420
to a company over privacy
concerns, meaning that seven

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:19.476
in ten Canadians, for example,
would not fill out a contact form

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:23.490
if they don't feel comfortable
or they don't receive

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:26.240
sufficient information about
what you will do with their PII.

00:10:27.460 --> 00:10:30.960
Accessible websites can also be
a competitive advantage as well.

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:35.440
So 75% of Americans with
disabilities report using the internet

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:36.660
on a daily basis.

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:39.980
And the market that includes
people with disabilities is estimated

00:10:39.980 --> 00:10:43.740
to control over $13 trillion
in annual disposable income,

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:45.976
which is huge for
business, right?

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.560
So if you have a website
that allows these people

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:53.860
to use your website to make
purchases or subscribe to emails

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:56.780
or whatever they want to
do, you are opening yourself

00:10:56.780 --> 00:10:57.820
up to a larger market.

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:01.160
<v Hans> There's two
more items too, and they kind

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:04.063
of go hand in hand, which is
avoiding fines and lawsuits.

00:11:04.470 --> 00:11:09.786
I'm sure throughout WordPress
Accessibility Day, this has been discussed;

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:11.950
and sure enough,
we're covering it as well.

00:11:12.630 --> 00:11:16.360
The fact is though is there are
privacy non-compliance fines.

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:19.200
There are one-person
marketing companies getting fined,

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:22.710
what was it, 60,000 euros
for changing the email address

00:11:22.710 --> 00:11:25.110
of one of their subscribers
without their consent.

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:30.146
And I think really what comes
into play here is that I think a lot

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:34.530
of people see in the news, like,
Facebook getting fined billions

00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:36.426
of dollars for privacy issues.

00:11:36.450 --> 00:11:39.870
But they don't see our small
businesses like one-person companies

00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:43.720
even getting fined for non-compliance
from a privacy standpoint.

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:46.910
So fines and lawsuits, I
mean, we have it listed here.

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:49.936
But really, the long
story short is, failure

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:54.990
to comply with applicable accessibility
laws and privacy laws can result

00:11:54.990 --> 00:11:57.420
in your business getting
into financial trouble as well.

00:11:57.420 --> 00:11:59.126
So it's not only
the right thing to do,

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:00.820
but not doing it actually
gets you in trouble.

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:04.390
So it's like double whammy
to stay focused on valuing this.

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:06.940
<v Donata> Yes, so privacy
law is currently enforced

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:10.050
by Data Protection Authorities
and attorney generals.

00:12:10.430 --> 00:12:14.570
So the fines for non-compliance
start $2,500 per violation,

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:18.320
meaning per website visitor whose
privacy rights have been infringed upon.

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:21.736
So let's say you have 100
website visitors from California

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:25.760
and you don't have a compliant
privacy policy, that fine is calculated

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:29.706
as 2,500 times 100, which
can add up really quickly.

00:12:29.730 --> 00:12:31.910
Although, there are also
proposed privacy bills

00:12:31.910 --> 00:12:35.330
that would allow consumers
to sue businesses of any size,

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:38.640
of any revenue, of any
employee size directly

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:40.886
for privacy law
violations as well.

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:44.090
So now we're seeing so
many accessibility lawsuits,

00:12:44.090 --> 00:12:46.450
but we're probably going
to see the same thing

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:49.150
with privacy once
these laws are passed.

00:12:49.150 --> 00:12:51.730
<v Hans> Yes. If I'm not mistaken, actually,

00:12:51.754 --> 00:12:54.776
lawsuits for accessibility
came out of New York.

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:58.036
And then sure enough, New
York has two bills out right now.

00:12:58.060 --> 00:13:01.066
If any of them pass, it
will enable any New Yorker

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:04.630
to sue any website owner for
collecting as little as an email address

00:13:04.630 --> 00:13:09.880
in a contact form without specific
New York privacy law disclosures.

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:12.610
So, yes, it's good motivation.

00:13:12.610 --> 00:13:14.774
It's the right thing to do
though is number one.

00:13:15.627 --> 00:13:18.446
<v Donata> So who needs
to follow privacy requirements?

00:13:18.470 --> 00:13:22.726
As Hans explained earlier, privacy
laws govern the collection, use,

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:26.060
and disclosure of personally
identifiable information.

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:30.076
So PII is any information
that could identify somebody,

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:33.370
or any information related
to an identified person.

00:13:33.370 --> 00:13:38.826
And examples of PII include names,
emails, phone numbers, IP addresses,

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:41.150
or physical addresses
such as the billing address.

00:13:41.650 --> 00:13:44.536
And those are commonly
collected through contact forms,

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:48.490
email newsletter subscription
forms, e-commerce forms, analytics,

00:13:48.490 --> 00:13:52.170
like Google analytics, or advertising
features like Facebook Pixel.

00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:55.360
What’s important to note
here is that privacy laws apply

00:13:55.360 --> 00:13:57.946
as soon as that information
is being collected.

00:13:57.970 --> 00:14:01.180
So you don't have to actually
use it, you don't have to disclose it,

00:14:01.180 --> 00:14:03.480
you don't need to share it,
and you don't need to sell it.

00:14:03.910 --> 00:14:06.280
The moment that that
information is being collected,

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:07.800
that's when privacy laws apply.

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:12.096
<v Hans> And just want to provide
a little footnote of education here.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:15.130
We have so many business owners
that say, Well, I don't share any

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:16.685
of the data I collect.

00:14:16.710 --> 00:14:20.896
And I like to always just make note
of an example that's very common.

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.930
If you have a contact form
on your website contact page

00:14:23.930 --> 00:14:26.790
and someone submits an
inquiry, and you receive an email

00:14:26.790 --> 00:14:29.450
in your inbox with that
person's contact details,

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:32.360
you've not only collected their
personal information like names

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:34.626
and emails, but you've
actually shared that data

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:38.060
with your email service provider,
whether it's G Suite, Gmail,

00:14:38.060 --> 00:14:43.036
Outlook, or any other third-party
email service system you use.

00:14:43.060 --> 00:14:45.520
So sharing data,
extremely common.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:48.106
What's not so
common is selling data.

00:14:48.130 --> 00:14:51.490
But sharing data, very common,
and that can be a required disclosure

00:14:51.556 --> 00:14:53.576
under certain privacy laws.

00:14:54.543 --> 00:14:57.480
<v Donata> So you will need
to follow privacy requirements

00:14:57.480 --> 00:15:01.580
if you collect PII, like names,
emails, phone numbers,

00:15:02.068 --> 00:15:06.320
and if privacy laws and their
requirements apply to you.

00:15:07.060 --> 00:15:10.276
Privacy laws do not apply to
every single business out there,

00:15:10.300 --> 00:15:13.280
but they protect consumers,
and they don't protect businesses.

00:15:13.690 --> 00:15:15.890
So that means that they
can apply to you regardless of

00:15:15.890 --> 00:15:18.980
whether you're located in the
state or country that passed that law.

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:22.456
And that's because of the
broad nature of the internet, right?

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:25.380
So people from anywhere could
submit their personal information

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:26.280
to your website.

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:29.160
So to figure out what
privacy laws apply to you,

00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:31.596
you should ask
yourself some questions.

00:15:31.620 --> 00:15:34.066
So whose PII are
you collecting online?

00:15:34.090 --> 00:15:35.670
Like, who's submitting
these forms?

00:15:36.090 --> 00:15:39.120
Who are you tracking online
through cookies, pixels, analytics?

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:41.810
So if you have those
features on your website,

00:15:42.210 --> 00:15:44.430
who's coming onto your
website and being tracked?

00:15:45.180 --> 00:15:47.157
Where are your
customers located?

00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:48.586
Where do you do business?

00:15:48.610 --> 00:15:51.066
And where do you
offer goods or services?

00:15:51.090 --> 00:15:55.230
So most privacy laws will apply to
businesses regardless of their revenue

00:15:55.230 --> 00:15:56.675
or employee size.

00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:58.686
So they will apply
to small businesses,

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:02.256
and a lot of privacy laws
actually apply to nonprofits as well.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:06.030
But some privacy laws will
exempt smaller businesses.

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:08.520
So it is important to first
determine what laws apply to you.

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:08.980
<v Hans> That's right.

00:16:08.980 --> 00:16:11.440
And just to reiterate,
because you have a website

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:14.070
and you could collect
inquiries from all over, it's good

00:16:14.070 --> 00:16:16.046
to remember privacy
laws protect people.

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:17.910
They don't care where
your business is located.

00:16:18.360 --> 00:16:21.350
And I know you just said it,
but I'd just like to say it louder.

00:16:22.930 --> 00:16:25.556
<v Donata> So there
are a lot of privacy laws

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:28.150
that govern the collection
of PII by websites.

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:30.850
We won't go through each and
every one of these because I don't want

00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:33.580
to bore you to death, but
just a couple examples.

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:37.250
So the California Online Privacy
and Protection Act, that applies

00:16:37.250 --> 00:16:40.876
to any business that collects the
personal information of residents

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:41.720
of California.

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:45.956
So people from California could
submit a form on your website,

00:16:45.980 --> 00:16:49.480
or you could collect their IP
address or like Facebook pixel,

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:51.250
you need to
comply with that law.

00:16:51.970 --> 00:16:55.970
Whereas other laws like Nevada
Revised Statute Chapter 603A,

00:16:56.350 --> 00:16:58.000
for that law to apply
to you, you will need

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.760
to collect the personal
information of residents of Nevada,

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:03.520
but you will also have to
do business in that state.

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:06.370
So as you can see, there are
different factors to determine

00:17:06.370 --> 00:17:08.580
which privacy laws
actually apply to you.

00:17:08.580 --> 00:17:12.230
And it's really funny because
since creating these slides,

00:17:12.230 --> 00:17:13.970
there's a new privacy
law that was passed,

00:17:13.970 --> 00:17:18.330
the Delaware Personal Data Protection
Act, which we haven't had a chance

00:17:18.330 --> 00:17:19.026
to add to that.

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:22.766
But I think that just kind of illustrates
how frequently these change.

00:17:22.790 --> 00:17:26.490
So there's over two dozen
privacy bills proposed in the U.S.

00:17:26.490 --> 00:17:29.560
Countries such as the
United Kingdom, Australia,

00:17:29.560 --> 00:17:33.076
and Canada are proposing
reform to their privacy laws

00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:36.950
because of new technologies
that create new privacy harms.

00:17:36.950 --> 00:17:38.646
So the laws have to keep up.

00:17:38.670 --> 00:17:40.350
So these things are
constantly changing.

00:17:40.350 --> 00:17:43.116
<v Hans> And really, I think
the big takeaway there is,

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:46.580
as a website owner, I used to
copy and paste privacy policies

00:17:46.580 --> 00:17:49.670
whenever I needed them, and
then I married a privacy attorney,

00:17:49.670 --> 00:17:51.546
so that obviously changed.

00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:55.100
But really, the takeaway
is I think the era of copying

00:17:55.100 --> 00:17:58.630
and pasting legal docs is not
only a terrible strategy upfront,

00:17:58.630 --> 00:18:01.510
because chances are you're
not compliant with the actual laws

00:18:01.510 --> 00:18:02.795
that apply to you.

00:18:02.820 --> 00:18:05.850
But also, it doesn't answer the
question of how do you keep your policies

00:18:05.850 --> 00:18:06.900
up to date over time?

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:08.980
This isn't a sales pitch.

00:18:08.980 --> 00:18:10.440
I mean, obviously,
talk to your attorney.

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:12.926
There are generators out
there like Termageddon 2.

00:18:12.950 --> 00:18:15.670
But really, the most important
thing is understanding

00:18:15.670 --> 00:18:18.610
that you can't just have a
privacy policy in this day and age.

00:18:18.610 --> 00:18:21.060
You have to have a strategy
to keep it up to date over time.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:22.842
<v Donata> Exactly.

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:26.490
So who needs to follow
accessibility requirements?

00:18:26.890 --> 00:18:30.580
So Title II of the ADA applies
to all services, programs,

00:18:30.580 --> 00:18:33.186
and activities of state
and local governments.

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:35.000
So if you're part of state
and local government,

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:36.620
you obviously
have to follow them.

00:18:37.080 --> 00:18:41.446
And Title III of the ADA applies
to businesses open to the public.

00:18:41.470 --> 00:18:44.946
So there is a case that
GIL versus Winn-Dixie Court

00:18:44.970 --> 00:18:48.150
that ruled that websites may
constitute public accommodations

00:18:48.570 --> 00:18:51.446
and therefore be
subject to the ADA.

00:18:51.470 --> 00:18:53.906
So those must be accessible.

00:18:53.930 --> 00:18:57.390
And although websites or apps
are not explicitly stated in the law,

00:18:57.860 --> 00:19:00.080
the online world is
increasingly being considered

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:03.860
as a public accommodation, and
there are a lot of cases that support that.

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:07.820
In the EU, we have the EU
Web Accessibility Directive

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:12.176
and the European Accessibility Act,
which requires public sector entities

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:14.940
and private companies to
provide accessible experiences

00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:16.170
for website visitors.

00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:19.686
The Accessible Canada Act
applies to any organizations

00:19:19.710 --> 00:19:22.170
under federal jurisdiction,
and the Australia

00:19:22.170 --> 00:19:25.620
Disability Discrimination Act
prohibits private and public sectors

00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:28.630
from discriminating against
people based on a disability.

00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:33.070
What's really interesting as a
privacy lawyer that I have seen recently

00:19:33.070 --> 00:19:35.870
in all of the new privacy
laws that I have been proposed

00:19:35.870 --> 00:19:40.310
and passed, is that they also
state that your website features

00:19:40.310 --> 00:19:43.540
that are privacy-focused
must be accessible as well.

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:46.326
Meaning that your privacy
policy must be accessible,

00:19:46.350 --> 00:19:48.660
your cookie consent
banner must be accessible,

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:51.436
and your cookie policy
must be accessible as well.

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:54.200
So it seems like the two
worlds are merging much more

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:58.000
than 10 years ago, where any
new laws passed didn't really talk

00:19:58.000 --> 00:19:59.770
about accessibility,
but they do now.

00:20:02.550 --> 00:20:05.980
So Hans, maybe you can
explain who needs a privacy policy?

00:20:05.980 --> 00:20:10.890
<v Hans> Sure. So a privacy policy
helps explain your privacy practices

00:20:11.330 --> 00:20:14.160
and it's usually created to
comply with privacy laws.

00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:18.146
So it all kind of starts with what
personal information you're collecting,

00:20:18.170 --> 00:20:19.800
what you're doing
with that information.

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:23.130
Like, I collected to contact
you, I collected for marketing

00:20:23.130 --> 00:20:24.725
or advertising.

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:28.380
Some privacy laws require you to
describe how you collect that information

00:20:28.380 --> 00:20:30.890
or who you may share
it with or if you sell it.

00:20:31.450 --> 00:20:38.536
Really, what it comes down to is
that a good privacy policy is created

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:40.386
if you know the laws
that apply to you,

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:43.930
because each privacy law lines
out exactly what you're supposed

00:20:43.930 --> 00:20:44.966
to disclose.

00:20:44.990 --> 00:20:47.560
So your very first step is to find
out the laws that apply to you.

00:20:48.200 --> 00:20:50.346
And then a privacy
policy from there needs

00:20:50.370 --> 00:20:54.120
to include the disclosures
required by those applicable laws.

00:20:54.680 --> 00:20:58.010
Your privacy must fit your actual
business and privacy practices.

00:20:58.010 --> 00:21:00.150
So I think that's one of
those concerns I have

00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:02.730
where people just copy and
paste legal documents like I used to,

00:21:02.730 --> 00:21:04.350
like, I didn't actually read it.

00:21:04.350 --> 00:21:06.830
I don't know if they actually
match my actual business

00:21:06.830 --> 00:21:08.655
and privacy practices.

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:11.686
And most importantly, they'd
need to stay up to date over time,

00:21:11.710 --> 00:21:14.356
as legislation constantly
changes in this space.

00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:17.370
<v Donata> Yes, and I
think it's important here to note

00:21:17.370 --> 00:21:19.700
that all privacy laws
require Websites

00:21:19.700 --> 00:21:22.126
to have a comprehensive
privacy policy.

00:21:22.150 --> 00:21:25.160
So if any of the privacy laws
apply to you, you will need

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:28.710
to have a privacy policy
that makes those disclosures.

00:21:30.610 --> 00:21:32.276
Who needs a cookie policy?

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:35.640
So the cookie policy, its
purpose is to inform users

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:38.556
about what cookies you
collect, why you collect them,

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:41.326
and how individuals can
exercise their privacy rights

00:21:41.350 --> 00:21:43.280
by changing their
cookie preferences.

00:21:43.650 --> 00:21:46.770
So for example, how can people
withdraw their consent to cookies

00:21:46.770 --> 00:21:49.970
that they have provided their
consent to before, which is required

00:21:49.970 --> 00:21:52.010
by applicable legislation.

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:56.450
So you will need a cookie policy,
or you can also have a privacy policy

00:21:56.450 --> 00:21:57.890
that discusses cookies.

00:21:58.530 --> 00:22:01.290
If your website collects cookies,
and if you need to comply

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:05.920
with the privacy directive, EU's
General Data Protection Regulation,

00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:10.180
UK's Data Protection Act, or
Canada's PIPEDA, because all

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:14.680
of these laws require businesses to
inform consumers what cookies are

00:22:14.680 --> 00:22:18.010
on a website, and how they
can exercise their cookie choices.

00:22:18.010 --> 00:22:20.290
<v Hans> And I'll also note,
you know, some of you may be,

00:22:20.290 --> 00:22:24.696
like, Well, you know, what
about CPRA or VCDPA?

00:22:24.720 --> 00:22:29.930
That is related to a notice that
website owners are required

00:22:29.930 --> 00:22:32.886
to provide if you sell the
information you collect.

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:34.510
So I think a lot of
people are surprised

00:22:34.510 --> 00:22:37.600
to hear that a cookie consent
banner is very different based on

00:22:37.600 --> 00:22:39.016
which law applies.

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:42.286
A California banner is to opt
out of the sale of the information,

00:22:42.310 --> 00:22:46.920
whereas a GDPR, ePrivacy
Directive banner for the EU is more

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:50.376
about giving people choices and
then being opted out by default,

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:53.760
and they have to consent to being
tracked for marketing purposes,

00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:54.330
for example.

00:22:54.330 --> 00:22:57.110
<v Donata> And CPRA does
not specifically require you

00:22:57.110 --> 00:23:00.620
to have a cookie consent
banner or a cookie policy.

00:23:01.260 --> 00:23:04.576
They do require you to have a
universal opt-out mechanism,

00:23:04.600 --> 00:23:08.346
and it just seems like everybody
chose to have a cookie consent banner.

00:23:08.370 --> 00:23:10.870
And that's what kind
of became the standard,

00:23:10.870 --> 00:23:13.330
but it's not actually
required by the law per se.

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:15.276
<v Hans> That's very true.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:20.010
<v Donata> In
that particular way.

00:23:20.010 --> 00:23:21.650
<v Hans> Yes, good call.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:24.606
Next, to meet the
requirements of privacy laws,

00:23:24.630 --> 00:23:29.366
privacy-related policies must be
posted conspicuously on a website,

00:23:29.390 --> 00:23:32.150
aka make your policy
links easily accessible.

00:23:33.630 --> 00:23:41.970
But a very clear requirement
when providing policies

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:44.040
on your website is
that they're accessible.

00:23:44.870 --> 00:23:47.070
We’re not talking about, you
know, putting them in your footer

00:23:47.070 --> 00:23:51.136
and having a black background
with super-dark gray text.

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:52.880
That is not conspicuous.

00:23:53.370 --> 00:23:55.500
Rather, you want it to
stand out, and make sure

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:57.460
that anyone can see
it from a mile away.

00:23:57.460 --> 00:23:59.260
<v Donata> Right, exactly.

00:23:59.640 --> 00:24:02.860
So conspicuous is kind
of a legal term, right?

00:24:03.453 --> 00:24:05.423
But what does
conspicuous actually mean?

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:09.996
To be conspicuous, a privacy
policy and a cookie policy,

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:14.500
they must be displayed in a way that
a reasonable person would notice it.

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:15.290
So what does that mean?

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:17.590
So first, the link to
the privacy policy

00:24:17.590 --> 00:24:20.300
and the cookie policy
should be posted on the footer

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:22.100
of every page of the website.

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:25.646
Meaning that if I navigate
from the homepage to the blog,

00:24:25.670 --> 00:24:27.100
it should still
be on the footer.

00:24:27.700 --> 00:24:31.036
The link should contain the
word privacy for privacy policy,

00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:32.870
and cookie for cookie policy.

00:24:33.230 --> 00:24:37.440
So that means that a link
that says policy is not sufficient

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:39.166
to be conspicuous.

00:24:39.190 --> 00:24:41.900
<v Hans> What about a link that
says legal, and then you're taken

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:43.610
to a page that
provides all the policies?

00:24:43.610 --> 00:24:46.080
<v Donata> Also not
conspicuous, because it needs

00:24:46.080 --> 00:24:47.410
to include the word privacy.

00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:51.080
So if it does not include the
word privacy, it is not conspicuous,

00:24:51.450 --> 00:24:55.176
because people don't
necessarily know what legal means.

00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:58.930
Like, does legal mean your BAT
number and your company address?

00:24:58.930 --> 00:25:00.666
Does it mean your
terms of service?

00:25:00.690 --> 00:25:01.940
Does it mean a contract?

00:25:01.940 --> 00:25:04.090
Does it mean your company
formation document?

00:25:04.090 --> 00:25:06.430
<v Hans> Does it mean that's where
the legal people go to read something?

00:25:06.430 --> 00:25:08.410
<v Donata> I mean, it
could be literally anything.

00:25:08.410 --> 00:25:11.560
So it does have to include the
word privacy for privacy policy,

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:13.140
and cookie for cookie policy.

00:25:13.850 --> 00:25:17.430
The privacy policy and cookie
policy should sit on separate pages.

00:25:17.430 --> 00:25:21.086
So do not combine a privacy
policy and the terms of service.

00:25:21.110 --> 00:25:22.926
Multiple privacy laws say this.

00:25:22.950 --> 00:25:27.030
In addition, if you have people
agree to privacy policy and the terms

00:25:27.030 --> 00:25:30.880
of service at the same time,
you actually cannot prove consent.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:33.656
It can also seem coercive.

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:35.800
So there's been certain
enforcement actions that said

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:42.866
that it's coercive to make a
user agree to privacy and terms

00:25:42.890 --> 00:25:46.750
at the same time, because
the user feels like they are

00:25:46.750 --> 00:25:50.560
being subject to contractual
requirements at the same time.

00:25:50.960 --> 00:25:52.640
So do not combine these two.

00:25:53.730 --> 00:25:57.656
Accessibility experts know this,
use contrasting type font or color

00:25:57.680 --> 00:25:59.760
from the surrounding
text if there is any.

00:26:00.340 --> 00:26:03.896
And use contrasting color of
the link as compared to the footer.

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:06.820
So basically make sure
that it's easily visible.

00:26:07.470 --> 00:26:10.760
And any forms where PII is
being submitted should contain

00:26:10.760 --> 00:26:14.420
a consent checkbox for individuals
to agree to the privacy policy.

00:26:14.810 --> 00:26:18.240
The box should not be pre-checked,
and it should be separate box

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:21.230
from an agreement to a
terms of service if you do decide

00:26:21.230 --> 00:26:23.330
to have a terms of
service agreement as well.

00:26:25.800 --> 00:26:29.930
OK, so now we're going to go into
my favorite part, which is examples.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:33.740
And what's really funny about
this is that when you search

00:26:33.740 --> 00:26:38.896
for examples, it will take you 20
