00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:04.380
who need to comply with
privacy laws that require them

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:07.580
to disclose whether
information is being sold.

00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:12.210
Now, in this first box, the
font is very clearly contrasted.

00:30:13.550 --> 00:30:16.300
The background is white
and then the text itself is black.

00:30:16.690 --> 00:30:18.006
So it's very easy to see.

00:30:18.030 --> 00:30:19.290
The font is large.

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:24.366
So most people can see it
without having to actually zoom in

00:30:24.390 --> 00:30:26.376
or anything like that.

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:30.160
On the second box, we have
another example of a privacy policy.

00:30:30.160 --> 00:30:35.446
So it says payment data, like
cardholder last name, date of card use.

00:30:35.470 --> 00:30:36.710
What do we use it for?

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:39.050
We use it in credit
card fraud prevention.

00:30:39.410 --> 00:30:43.756
Now, this example is actually not
great because of very low contrast.

00:30:43.780 --> 00:30:47.266
So because of this low contrast
between the background and the font,

00:30:47.290 --> 00:30:48.700
it's very hard to see.

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:55.430
And when you actually
look at it in a privacy policy,

00:30:55.430 --> 00:31:00.250
the font is really small,
the contrast is really low,

00:31:00.250 --> 00:31:02.150
so it's very hard
to read for people.

00:31:02.550 --> 00:31:03.990
This is true for anybody, right?

00:31:03.990 --> 00:31:07.150
It's hard to read for people
with disabilities, but it's also hard

00:31:07.150 --> 00:31:09.090
to read for anyone else as well.

00:31:09.090 --> 00:31:12.080
You don't want people to
have to strain their eyes, zoom in

00:31:12.080 --> 00:31:15.700
and zoom out, and go through all of
this to see their privacy information.

00:31:15.700 --> 00:31:20.280
And that's why not just the way
you display the privacy policy link

00:31:20.280 --> 00:31:23.486
is important, but the way
that your privacy policy itself,

00:31:23.510 --> 00:31:27.301
the text appears on your
website, is very important as well.

00:31:29.001 --> 00:31:33.980
<v Hans> So a lot of people have
questions around cookie consent banners,

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:36.946
and who needs
one in the first place.

00:31:36.970 --> 00:31:40.960
So I think we did discuss earlier
that cookie consent banners required

00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:44.750
under the ePrivacy Directive,
GDPR, which protects residents

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:48.340
of the EU, the UK Data
Protection Act, Canada's PIPEDA,

00:31:49.030 --> 00:31:51.760
California's CPRA,
and Virginia's VCDPA.

00:31:52.620 --> 00:31:56.020
A cookie consent banner is a
mechanism that allows websites

00:31:56.020 --> 00:32:00.030
to respect your user's privacy
rights by requiring their consent

00:32:00.030 --> 00:32:02.876
to be provided prior to the
application of certain cookies

00:32:02.900 --> 00:32:04.640
being placed on
the user's browser.

00:32:05.250 --> 00:32:07.940
And really, what this means
is if you have, let's say,

00:32:07.940 --> 00:32:11.680
Hotjar analytics, which
is an excellent example

00:32:11.680 --> 00:32:14.826
where you're understanding
how people use your website,

00:32:14.850 --> 00:32:17.236
and there's absolutely
nothing wrong with that.

00:32:17.260 --> 00:32:21.000
But what's important to remind
yourself of is that privacy laws protect

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:25.396
and regulate the ability
to just willy-nilly do that.

00:32:25.420 --> 00:32:30.310
Rather, you have to get consent
first before you can allow Hotjar

00:32:30.310 --> 00:32:34.000
to operate and start analyzing
visitors visiting your website.

00:32:34.680 --> 00:32:37.800
And that's the ePrivacy
Directive, GDPR,

00:32:37.800 --> 00:32:40.000
and the UK Data
Protection Act, and PIPEDA.

00:32:40.610 --> 00:32:44.240
However, CPRA has a
modified cookie consent banner,

00:32:44.240 --> 00:32:47.980
as well as VCDPA, where it is
an opt out of sale of information.

00:32:47.980 --> 00:32:51.276
<v Donata> And to
actually obtain consent.

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:54.436
So consent is also
a legal term, right?

00:32:54.460 --> 00:32:57.300
So to actually obtain consent,
the user must be presented

00:32:57.300 --> 00:33:00.176
with an accept and
a decline option.

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:02.736
So that means that you have to
have an option that says accept

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:04.980
and an option that says
decline, and they both have

00:33:04.980 --> 00:33:06.310
to be equally prominent.

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:09.470
Now inactivity,
meaning doing nothing,

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:11.680
does not actually
constitute consent.

00:33:12.080 --> 00:33:15.230
So all of the cookie consent
banners that just say, OK,

00:33:15.230 --> 00:33:18.490
or, By using this website, we
assume that you're OK with cookies,

00:33:18.910 --> 00:33:22.606
that is not actually proper
consent, and that is a violation

00:33:22.630 --> 00:33:23.130
of these laws.

00:33:23.130 --> 00:33:26.610
<v Hans> And these companies
that have been dinged eight figures,

00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:27.306
if I'm not mistaken.

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:28.250
<v Donata> That's right.
Yes.

00:33:28.650 --> 00:33:30.930
So we'll show you some
examples here as well.

00:33:31.910 --> 00:33:34.040
But what's important
here to remember,

00:33:34.040 --> 00:33:37.870
cookie consent banners must
control all non-essential cookies

00:33:37.870 --> 00:33:40.850
to not fire until the user
provides their consent.

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:44.220
Now, essential cookies, which
are essential to the operation

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:46.910
of the website, meaning
that without these cookies,

00:33:46.910 --> 00:33:50.126
the website would break,
those do not need consent.

00:33:50.150 --> 00:33:54.356
However, any marketing or functional
cookies or advertising cookies,

00:33:54.380 --> 00:33:57.660
they cannot fire until the user
provides their actual consent.

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:02.980
So how to display your
cookie consent banner?

00:34:03.490 --> 00:34:07.470
So here we have a cookie consent
banner that says privacy settings:

00:34:07.470 --> 00:34:10.806
We use third-party website
tracking technologies to provide

00:34:10.830 --> 00:34:13.540
and continually improve your
experience on our website.

00:34:13.950 --> 00:34:16.880
You can revoke or change
your consent at any time.

00:34:17.240 --> 00:34:18.850
It links to a privacy policy.

00:34:18.850 --> 00:34:22.290
It also links to more information,
which leads to a cookie policy.

00:34:22.770 --> 00:34:24.620
Then it has toggle tags.

00:34:24.620 --> 00:34:28.356
So one tag is marketing,
which is turned off.

00:34:28.380 --> 00:34:30.870
Another tag is functional,
which is turned off.

00:34:31.330 --> 00:34:36.306
And another tag is essential, which
is always turned on per regulations.

00:34:36.330 --> 00:34:37.640
So here you can make a choice.

00:34:37.640 --> 00:34:40.976
You can accept all, meaning
that you accept all cookies.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:42.910
You can toggle
marketing or functional.

00:34:42.910 --> 00:34:45.420
So let's say I only want
functional, I can turn that on.

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:48.066
I only want marketing,
I can turn that on.

00:34:48.090 --> 00:34:51.700
You can click deny, which means
that no cookies will be turned on

00:34:51.700 --> 00:34:52.730
except essential.

00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:55.120
And then you can
also save your settings.

00:34:55.620 --> 00:34:57.920
Now what's important to
note here is that accept all

00:34:57.920 --> 00:35:00.696
and deny both have
the same prominence.

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:04.510
So they are both large purple
buttons of the same color

00:35:04.510 --> 00:35:06.336
with the text being in white.

00:35:06.360 --> 00:35:08.900
And that's very important
because you're not tricking the user

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:09.730
into agreeing.

00:35:10.110 --> 00:35:14.150
So if you had accept all
in green and deny in white,

00:35:14.150 --> 00:35:18.000
let's say, that would be
considered a dark pattern

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.170
because it tricks the
user into consenting,

00:35:20.170 --> 00:35:22.120
which is not
actual real consent.

00:35:22.910 --> 00:35:25.990
Then on the right, we have
a purple fingerprint icon.

00:35:26.520 --> 00:35:29.650
So what happens with cookies is
that users have the right to consent

00:35:29.650 --> 00:35:32.800
to cookies, and they also have
the right to withdraw their consent.

00:35:33.160 --> 00:35:36.370
So let's say yesterday I agreed
to a Facebook pixel to track me;

00:35:37.140 --> 00:35:39.390
and today I decide no, I
actually don't want that,

00:35:39.390 --> 00:35:42.196
I have the right to go in
and change my settings.

00:35:42.220 --> 00:35:45.140
So what I do here with this
particular cookie consent banner

00:35:45.140 --> 00:35:48.836
is I will click on the fingerprint
icon, and then I can unselect

00:35:48.860 --> 00:35:52.910
or reselect any cookies that I want
and change my options at any time.

00:35:55.839 --> 00:35:59.010
<v Hans> Now, how not to
display your cookie consent banner,

00:35:59.010 --> 00:36:00.810
and hopefully everyone's
finding this interesting.

00:36:00.810 --> 00:36:04.070
I'll let you know, like, once you
learn this, it becomes interesting going

00:36:04.070 --> 00:36:06.380
to websites and being like,
Oh, you're not compliant.

00:36:06.380 --> 00:36:07.460
<v Donata> It is fun.

00:36:07.940 --> 00:36:11.290
If you are ever bored or
have a hard time falling asleep,

00:36:11.720 --> 00:36:14.350
check out Dark
Patterns Hall of Shame.

00:36:14.890 --> 00:36:18.926
So that's actually a website that
aggregates all of these violations

00:36:18.950 --> 00:36:20.230
and shames companies.

00:36:20.680 --> 00:36:23.930
And there's also really interesting
E-commerce dark patterns,

00:36:23.930 --> 00:36:28.156
which I love looking at of how people
trick people into making a purchase.

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:31.936
<v Hans> Well, and sure enough,
with this example we have listed here,

00:36:31.960 --> 00:36:35.230
we have what looks to be a
pretty big consent banner saying,

00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:37.250
we care about your privacy,
and going on to distribute it.

00:36:37.250 --> 00:36:38.020
<v Donata> Do you though?

00:36:38.020 --> 00:36:38.160
Do you?

00:36:38.160 --> 00:36:39.765
<v Hans> [chuckles]
Yes, no kidding.

00:36:39.790 --> 00:36:42.640
And then, We and partners
process data to provide

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:46.710
And they list a bunch of
purposes as why they process data.

00:36:47.380 --> 00:36:51.846
But the problem here is that
we have a big blue I accept button

00:36:51.870 --> 00:36:55.000
that quickly captures
your attention; you want

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:56.750
to just click it almost
right out the gate.

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:01.260
And then there's show purposes,
which is an underlined hyperlink

00:37:02.520 --> 00:37:05.916
with a white background and just
the word show purposes in blue.

00:37:05.940 --> 00:37:09.576
So it's very clearly drawing your
attention to an I accept button,

00:37:09.600 --> 00:37:14.536
but as we just learned, you need
to have a clear deny option as well.

00:37:14.560 --> 00:37:17.560
You got to remember, certain
privacy laws allow people

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:20.846
to not be tracked by default,
meaning they have to consent

00:37:20.870 --> 00:37:24.716
to your website first before
you're allowed to start tracking them

00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:27.206
or placing non-essential
cookies on their browsers.

00:37:27.230 --> 00:37:30.620
So this is a deceptive cookie
consent banner because they're trying

00:37:30.620 --> 00:37:33.416
to encourage you to
forfeit your privacy rights

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:35.340
by clicking that
blue I accept button.

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:37.150
<v Donata> Yes, and
there's no deny button.

00:37:37.150 --> 00:37:39.450
It's only show purposes,
which is not deny.

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:42.750
Show purposes is, Show me a
list of why you need these cookies,

00:37:42.750 --> 00:37:43.940
not actually deny them.

00:37:44.530 --> 00:37:47.300
So this is a perfect example
of a non-compliant banner.

00:37:47.300 --> 00:37:51.440
<v Hans> Here we have
another example of how not

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:53.206
to display your
cookie consent banner.

00:37:53.230 --> 00:37:56.270
So the previous example is
bad, but this one's even worse

00:37:57.140 --> 00:38:02.046
in the sense that this screenshot
is of a giant accept button.

00:38:02.070 --> 00:38:04.760
It says, We need your consent
to set cookies on your device.

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:06.840
To agree, click ‘accept’ below.

00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:11.810
And the accept button takes
up like 30% of the bottom half

00:38:11.810 --> 00:38:12.350
of this thing.

00:38:12.830 --> 00:38:16.100
Then in the bottom left corner
is a tiny little reject button,

00:38:16.100 --> 00:38:18.660
and then a more information
button in the bottom right corner.

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:21.870
So this is very clear that the
company is trying to encourage you

00:38:21.870 --> 00:38:24.860
to forfeit your privacy rights in
exchange for them being able

00:38:24.860 --> 00:38:26.270
to track you and so forth.

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:28.120
And this is the
type of dark patterns

00:38:28.120 --> 00:38:30.440
that have gotten
companies fined significantly.

00:38:30.440 --> 00:38:33.460
<v Donata> Yes, and there's
another two problems here.

00:38:33.460 --> 00:38:37.286
So, again, we blew up this
screenshot so that it'd be easier to see,

00:38:37.310 --> 00:38:41.150
but in real life, the
reject button was tiny.

00:38:41.610 --> 00:38:45.060
So it's definitely not accessible
because the font was not large enough.

00:38:45.460 --> 00:38:48.810
The problem here, too, is We
need your consent to set cookies

00:38:48.810 --> 00:38:49.590
on your device.

00:38:49.950 --> 00:38:52.370
Do you mean you
would like your consent?

00:38:52.850 --> 00:38:56.120
It's almost making you
feel like you have to consent,

00:38:56.120 --> 00:38:57.800
when in reality,
you really don't.

00:38:58.400 --> 00:39:01.180
So there's problems with
the verbiage, and also the way

00:39:01.180 --> 00:39:03.308
that this is set up as well.

00:39:03.858 --> 00:39:06.506
This one is one of my favorites.

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:09.350
So this one makes it
essentially impossible for a user

00:39:09.350 --> 00:39:12.450
